<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-633-045  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 633 045.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Nov 19 1990 v4 n39 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AWIPS-90 bids get finishing touches. (National Weather Service'sAdvanced Weather Interactive Processing System for the 1990s)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marsan, Carolyn Duffy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Weather Service will be taking bids on its $500million Advanced Weather Interactive Processing System for the1990s (AWIPS-90) which will automate the compilation of weatherdata and will improve the Service's ability to forecast dangerousweather conditions.andP;  Its components include Unisys Corp'sNext-Generation Weather Radar network of Doppler radars, AAICorp's Automated Surface Observation System ground-based sensorsand two weather satellites.andP;  Computer Sciences Corp and PlanningResearch have each spent more than $1 million developingprototypes for AWIPS-90.andP;  Computer Sciences Corp and IBM willprovide hardware support; GE American Communications and GTESpacenet will provide satellite communications.andP;  Planning ResearchCorp is using computers from HP and other suppliers.andP;  AWIPS-90calls for 1,000 scientific workstations with satellite imaging,graphics, radar image, and text capabilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Sciences Corp. (Contracts)Planning Research Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    CSC.andO;Topic:     United States. National Weather ServiceSatellite CommunicationsRadar SystemsGovernment ContractsGeographic Information Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>